@skhoroshavin 

> This was a lot of work, however this still has two serious problems:
>pool_install.yml doesn't work with inventory created with inventory_init.py mypool and updated with >ansible-playbook -i mypool pool_create.yml
There were two reasons:
1. ssh configs polluted inventory directory (as you mentioned). Fixed
2. `pool_install` play used `nodes` group but it didn't have any relations with `pool_create` play vars. Fixed
>it's great that inventory_init.py looks for defaults in roles in very generic way, however it would be much >more convenient if it automatically updated aws_tag_namespace accordingly. Yes, it can be updated >manually or with yet another parameter to inventory_init, but it looks odd and I fear this workflow will be >error-prone

Fixed: namespace now is a basename of the inventory if the latter is defined (default is the same)

Are we sure about a requirement to deprecate Vagrant? Maybe we should rather fix the scripts?
I'm also not sure that `CloudFormation` works properly.

Nathan, I, and others at Sovrin have discussed that it makes more sense to offer one widely support and documented way of running the test network. None of the devs at Sovrin have successfully been able to run it, but Docker works well for all of us. 

I removed it from the newbie documentation and labeled it as 'deprecated' elsewhere, but it still exists for those who want to use it. (And if someone wants to fix the scripts and get it working again, by all means they can go ahead).
None of us have used `CloudFormation` either so it may also be worth deprecating.

According to PEP 8 the maximum allowed line length is 79 characters. Please correct the line wrapping in all your sources correspondingly.

@nghia47 Please see the comment above about the content of `indy-node/acceptance/pool.txn`.

@spivachuk We are using a Vagrant environment for this test so moving to Docker will take a couple of time.

@StevenL2015 Please confirm the moving.
@nghia47 @StevenL2015 If we run acceptance tests with Vagrant environment then genesis pool transactions for `indy-node/acceptance/pool.txn` can be taken from Vagrant.

@spivachuk 
Is it possible to update the content of exited pool.txn file with the Vagrant machine IP? Or we should mention that user has to check their environment IPs then update the pool with correct ones. Please advice.

@nghia47 You can update `pool.txn` content in accordance with Vagrant environment. In addition please add a note to `README.md` about the acceptance tests are run against the pool from Vagrant environment by default and the user has to update `pool.txn` content if they want to run the tests against another pool.

@spivachuk @ashcherbakov 
We just found a suitable location for this acceptance test and will use it from now on. Thank you for your comments and supporting. Please help to reject this pull request.
@nghia47 You are welcome. Closed this pull request as requested.
